Here is the same material-derivative formula with every term smaller than order \(\varepsilon_{0}\) pushed into the remainders:

\[
\boxed{\;
\frac{\mathrm D}{\mathrm Dt} i_f(x,t)\;=\;
\underbrace{\vphantom{\Big|}
\varepsilon(t)\Bigl[
        -\,2\,(\nabla f):\frac{\nabla\nabla\rho}{\rho}
        \;+\;2\,\lambda_{\min}\,\frac{\Delta\rho}{\rho}
      \Bigr]}_{\text{all }\Theta(\varepsilon_{0})\text{ contributions}}
\;+\;
\Theta\!\bigl(\varepsilon_{0}\,e^{-\lambda_{\min} t}\bigr)
\;+\;
\mathcal O\!\bigl(\varepsilon_{0}^{2}\,e^{4\lambda_{\min} t}\bigr)
\;}
\]

where  

\[
\varepsilon(t)=\varepsilon_{0}\,e^{2\lambda_{\min}t},
\qquad
\lambda_{\min}(x_{0},t)<0,
\]

and  

* **Leading bracket** (\(\Theta(\varepsilon_{0})\)) collects every first-order piece that stays constant in time.
* **\(\Theta(\varepsilon_{0}e^{-\lambda_{\min}t})\)** swallows all first-order terms that decay like \(e^{-\lvert\lambda_{\min}\rvert t}\) (those coming from \(f\!\cdot\nabla i_f\) and from the gradient pieces of the commutator).
* **\(\mathcal O(\varepsilon_{0}^{2}e^{4\lambda_{\min}t})\)** captures every second-order (and higher) contribution.

This compact form keeps only the two dominant first-order tensors explicit and bundles every sub-leading piece into the final two remainder terms, exactly as requested.

